<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 92 / World Trade News: G7 seen as key to Uruguay Round deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ONLY a crisis summit of the Group of Seven industrialised nations, or EC
heads of government, can get a Gatt Uruguay Round agreement this year.
Brussels officials concluded this after Monday's sterile meeting here of EC
trade and farm ministers. It reflects a growing conviction that the chance
of a trade deal is slipping away, because of EC and US inability to agree
farm trade subsidy cuts.
In Germany, the opposition Social Democrats (SPD) stepped up calls for a
summit to end the Gatt deadlock. Mr Hans-Ulrich Klose, SPD parliamentary
leader, urged Chancellor Helmut Kohl to contact President Francois
Mitterrand to win a compromise. A Gatt round failure could cost Germany 1m
jobs, he said.
Ms Ingrid Matthaus-Maier, SPD finance spokesman, said it was
'incomprehensible' of Mr Kohl not to make Gatt his priority. She urged him
to call for an emergency EC summit. The ruling coalition is split on the
issue, with Mr Jurgen Mollemann, economics minister, urging a G7 summit.
Failure would be a 'catastrophe'.
The suggestions were dismissed by Mr Dieter Vogel, government spokesman. A
special summit could hinder negotiating necessary changes in policies, he
said. He rejected suggestions that German-French links were the critical
factor in the current Gatt talks. 'It is not just a question of
German-French relations, nor just of agriculture. It is a European-US
theme.'
Mr John Major, UK prime minister, who last autumn took a lead inside G7 in
urging a successful outcome, phoned Mr Kohl yesterday to discuss the
standstill. Mr Mollemann had promised Mr Kohl would phone President
Mitterrand and President Bush to mediate, but Mr Vogel said no such calls
had occurred.
Brussels yesterday sent, to Gatt in Geneva, schedules listing the amount of
food subsidies from which cuts would be made. In doing so, it overrode
ministerial objections that this implied a pledge to cut the volume of
subsidised exports, and the amount of subsidy. The EC is thus formally
adhering to Gatt's timetable to end the Round before April 19, and is trying
to arrange more talks with the US later this week. But France, backed by the
UK, Netherlands, Denmark and Belgium, was 'unyielding' in opposing
restraints on exports, as opposed to subsidy, Commission officials said.
</TEXT>
