<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 92 / Brady makes strong plea on IMF quotas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bush administration yesterday renewed its efforts to win approval from
Congress for its Dollars 12bn share of the International Monetary Fund's
capital increase.
Mr Nicholas Brady, treasury secretary, made a strong appeal for Congress to
pass 'this all-important legislation'.
He warned that failure to do so would block the entire Dollars 60bn quota
increase and 'seriously impede the west's entire response to the new states
of the former Soviet Union'.
Mr Brady said the IMF aid programme for the Russian republic alone would
cost roughly Dollars 4bn.
'We simply shouldn't take a chance at this particular point in time with
abandoning the democratic changes that are taking place in the republics
which formerly constituted the Soviet Union,' he said.
</TEXT>
