<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 92 / Hong Kong to leave China higher reserves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HONG KONG is planning to leave to China an accumulated budget surplus nearly
two and a half times the level promised by Britain last September in an
accord between the two countries.
Mr Hamish MacLeod, Hong Kong's financial secretary, said in his maiden
budget yesterday that by March 1997 the government planned to have
accumulated fiscal reserves of HKDollars 71.6bn (Pounds 5.26bn). Hong Kong
reverts to Chinese sovereignty on July 1, 1997.
Last September Mr John Major, the British prime minister, undertook to leave
the new Hong Kong government with reserves of HKDollars 25bn, including
outstanding debt no greater than HkDollars 5bn. This pledge came amid
agreement with Beijing that the colony could build a HKDollars 100bn airport
and related infrastructure projects.
Mr MacLeod said that at the end of March 1997 the colony's reserves would
amount to HKDollars 62.8bn and outstanding debt, which is included in
reserves, would be HkDollars 4.8bn.
To achieve this outcome he raised the corporate tax rate to 17.5 per cent
from 16.5 per cent, despite having a large budget surplus.
It is understood that the Hong Kong government wanted a sizeable fiscal
cushion up until 1997 to ensure that unforeseeable events, such as a
worsening in the world economy, troubles in China, or a loss of investor
confidence in the colony did not leave it unable to meet its spending plans.
Mr MacLeod said in his budget speech that the projected level of reserves
would also have the additional advantage of demonstrating the colony's
financial strength and prudence. 'This should do much to reassure potential
lenders at a time when we shall be financing our infrastructural
development,' he said.
His forecast for the level of reserves are based on 5 per cent real growth
in the Hong Kong economy over the next five years and inflation, as measured
by the gross domestic product deflator, rising at an annual rate of 8.5 per
cent during that period. Consumer price inflation is expected to rise at a
faster rate.
The forecasts appear to be based on no significant changes to the cost of
the airport and related developments. Many of these projects are close to
the limits of technology, and are planned on an extremely tight time scale.
Some time slippage has already occurred.
The government's capital spending and related equity commitments connected
with the airport development are set to balloon from the 1993-94 fiscal year
on. This increase in capital spending will push the colony's public finances
into deficit - the first time in years that the government will run a
deficit not brought about by a downturn in the economic cycle.
On the capital side, the government is planning to spend HKDollars 176.5bn
of which HKDollars 44bn is attributable to the airport.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
