<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 92 / Manila strikes deal with Westinghouse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Philippine government and Westinghouse Electric, the US conglomerate,
yesterday reached an out-of-court settlement of a long-running suit alleging
that the company bribed the late President Ferdinand Marcos to build a power
station.
The settlement, which also includes Burns &amp; Roe, a US consultant to
Westinghouse, came the day before the case was due to be heard by a jury in
a federal court in the state of New Jersey. A month ago Westinghouse failed
in a federal court appeal to get the bribery and corruption charges against
it dropped.
Both sides yesterday claimed to be satisfied with the complex settlement to
the deal, which involves Westinghouse giving Dollars 100m (Pounds 56.8m) in
concessions to the Philippines government and the government giving
Westinghouse Dollars 400m to upgrade the plant at the centre of the dispute.
The case involves a contract to build a 620MW power station on the
Philippines' Bataan peninsula, which was completed in 1986 but never used.
The government and its National Power Corporation filed suit in the US in
1988 claiming the contract was won as a result of Dollars 17m in bribes paid
to former President Marcos.
Under the terms of yesterday's settlement, the Philippines has hired
Westinghouse to rehabilitate the plant and operate it for 30 years. The
company will get an annual fee of Dollars 40m and the Philippines government
will provide Dollars 400m for the upgrade, to be borrowed from the US
Export-Import bank.
Westinghouse will net some Dollars 300m after providing the Philippines with
around Dollars 100m in cash and discounts. Mr David Boies, lead counsel for
Westinghouse, said it was a 'win win situation. The Philippines is getting a
good plant and electricity and Westinghouse is getting the opportunity to
see it operate'.
Some technical parts of the case were also being heard by the International
Chamber of Commerce in Geneva which issued a preliminary finding in December
that there was no evidence bribes were paid to win the contract.
</TEXT>
