<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 92 / First class travellers may avoid queues at Heathrow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FIRST CLASS and business class passengers flying into London's Heathrow
airport could have their own express queues for immigration controls, under
a plan put forward by airlines.
They have told the Home Office they would be prepared to pay for extra
immigration staff to speed up formalities for first and business class
passengers.
The Home Office said yesterday it was examining the proposal, which is aimed
at reducing immigration queues for non-European Community nationals. The
queues are particularly long in the early morning when flights arrive from
North America and the Far East. The suggestion has received the backing of
the British Tourist Authority.
Previous attempts by airlines to reduce Heathrow immigration queues have
foundered because the Home Office has said it does not have enough money for
additional staff. British Airways, one of the airlines behind the move, said
the offer was an attempt to overcome this difficulty.
Although the airlines would bear the cost of the extra officers, they would
remain under Home Office control. BA said that the proposal was the first
step in an attempt to shorten waiting times for passengers.
The Home Office said that because airline funding would result in an
increase in staffing it did not expect any union opposition to the proposal.
The Home Office said the plan had been supported by several airlines using
Heathrow, but not all. United Airlines, the US carrier, said it was in
favour of speeding up Heathrow immigration formalities but did not see why
it should have to bear the cost.
The Home Office said it was also looking at allowing visitors to clear UK
immigration before boarding. This would involve stationing British
immigration officers at airports in New York or Tokyo.
The British Tourist Authority has also suggested having a separate queue at
UK airports for non-EC nationals who are resident in Britain.
BAA, the company which owns Heathrow, said a survey conducted at Terminal 3
last summer revealed significantly longer waiting times for non-EC nationals
arriving on early morning flights.
