<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 92 / UK Company News: Acquisitive Heywood Williams falls to
Pounds 19.2m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HEYWOOD WILLIAMS, the UK's largest glass distributor, yesterday announced
its seventh acquisition since last year's Pounds 28m rights issue as it
unveiled a 17 per cent drop in pre-tax profits for the year ended December
31 1991.
The profits fall, from Pounds 23.1m to Pounds 19.2m, was struck on turnover
up by 5 per cent from Pounds 331.5m to Pounds 347.4m and was mainly due to
the depressed state of the UK construction industry.
Mr Ralph Hinchliffe, Heywood's chairman, said: 'The whole of the fall can be
put down to aluminium and glass connected with commercial buildings.' He
added that there were no real signs of an upturn in the UK.
The result, helped by last year's acquisition of Thurgar Bardex, the
Kettering-based manufacturer of windows and doors, was still above market
expectations. The shares rose 8p to close at 331p.
Door Panels Group, a manufacturer of plastic door panels bought for Pounds
7.8m, will be incorporated into the group's growing plastics division, which
presently accounts for one quarter of total sales.
Continental operations finished well ahead of 1990 and have recently been
boosted by two new businesses in The Netherlands and France.
The group's US businesses were only just behind their 1990 result.
The UK workforce was reduced by 420 to a total of 5,380. In the US the
Georgia manufacturing plant was closed and several glass operations in the
UK were amalgamated.
Borrowings have fallen slightly to Pounds 20m, representing 20 per cent of
shareholders' funds.
Earnings per share fell from an adjusted 22.8p to 17.2p. A final dividend of
8p is proposed, making a total for the year of 12.5p (12p adjusted).
COMMENT
There is not much Heywood Williams can do about depressed demand in one of
its main businesses. Apart from a pick up in the home improvement market in
the second half there is little chance of a significant upturn in UK housing
or construction. The group has taken advantage of the low prices of plastic
and glass business during the recession by snapping up seven companies in
its last financial year. The plastics division is growing in size and
profitability while the Continental glass operations are also providing
better results. With expected full-year profits for 1992 of Pounds 26m,
giving earnings per share of 21.1, the shares are trading on a prospective
multiple of 15.6 compared to a sector average of 18.2. Given the expected
increase in profits the shares look good value.
</TEXT>
