   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC Enterprises, the commercial arm of the BBC, has bought the rights to
Enid Blyton's Noddy books from the administrator of Maxwell Communication
Corporation.
The 24 Noddy titles, published by Queen Anne's Press, were part of
Macdonald, MCC's UK book subsidiary. Price Waterhouse, appointed MCC's
administrator last year after the collapse of the late Mr Robert Maxwell's
business empire, last month sold the rest of Macdonald. However the buyer,
Little Brown, a US publisher specialising in art books, declined to take the
Noddy titles.
The BBC has commissioned a Noddy cartoon series from Cosgrove Hall, the
cartoon-making arm of Thames Television, which currently holds the franchise
for London weekday broadcasting.
