<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Can you bring yourself to watch the first episode of The Big One on C4? This
new comedy series with Mike McShane and Sandi Toksvig (whose name, like
Trebor, should surely be read backwards) has been so insistently trailed
that I have already developed a mild hostility towards it. McShane and
Givskot are known from 'Whose Line Is It Anyway?', the improvisation show
from which an endless succession of very variable comedies is spinning off.
She is the small, very funny, one and he is big and rather less funny. In
The Big One he plays a successful and tidy American writer who comes to stay
with her, the unusccessful and untidy English writer (8.30). That is
followed by the opening episode of a 4-part adaptation of Mary Wesley's
English family saga The Camomile Lawn (9.00). It follows the fortunes of
five cousins, from the summer of 1939 when they gather on the lawn behind
their aunt's Cornish house, to 1984. Paul Eddington and Felicity Kendal star
and the direction is by Peter Hall.
The last in BBC2's interesting, if patchy, documentary series about Spain,
Fire In The Blood looks at Barcelona, one of Europe's most fashionable
cities, and the venue for the 1992 Olympic games.
</TEXT>
