FT  05 MAR 92 / Minimum wage will be costly, says CBI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR'S proposed minimum wage would raise unemployment by at least 150,000
and add more than Pounds 2.5bn a year to employment costs, the Confederation
of British Industry said yesterday.
The CBI renewed its onslaught on Labour's plans, warning that they
threatened to destroy a number of industries which are already struggling in
the recession.
Sir John Banham, CBI director-general, said that a minimum wage would mean
the profits of some sectors were completely wiped out. There was particular
concern about textiles, clothing footwear, tourism and agriculture.
The CBI's criticisms lend some support to the claims from the government
about the impact of a minimum wage, although Mr Michael Howard, the
employment secretary, has said Labour's policy could mean 2m job losses.
A CBI document put to the organisation's council estimated that a minimum
wage would affect up to 3.4m jobs, including most of the 1.1m part-time jobs
created during the last decade.
