<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 92 / Watchdog seeks Imro explanation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief investment watchdog,
has asked Imro, the self-regulatory body for fund managers, for a report
explaining how it regulated investment companies owned by the late Mr Robert
Maxwell.
The move comes as a parliamentary committee prepares to release its report
on hearings into the Maxwell company pension schemes in which Imro (the
Investment Management Regulatory Organisation) will bear the brunt of fierce
criticism for regulatory failure.
In particular, SIB wants to know why Imro approved Bishopsgate Investment
Management as an occupational pension scheme member under section 191 of its
rulebook - a section that subjected it to a much looser regulatory regime
than other fund managers. Of Imro's roughly 1,200 members, 170 are in this
category.
Imro had initially intended section 191 to apply only to those trustees who
managed investment business on a day-to-day basis. Eventually the category
was extended to cover fund-management companies owned by the employer or
'any company whose relationship to the scheme was such that Imro felt this
chapter should apply'.
Of the nine directors of BIM, only four were pension-fund trustees and BIM
was not owned by the companies whose pension schemes it managed. Thus, SIB
has asked how Imro saw BIM as a suitable candidate for less stringent rules,
particularly in light of its initial unease about approving the company.
Mr John Morgan, chief executive of Imro, said yesterday in an interview with
the Financial Times that the self-regulatory body is reviewing its
application of section 191 to pension fund managers.
Meanwhile, Mr Morgan called for a new pensions act to clarify the
obligations and duties of trustees and their relationship to investment
business. 'It seems to me that it (a new pensions act) is inescapable,' Mr
Morgan said. 'It is a bit simple-minded to argue that a few good ideas will
solve everything.'
There are signs of growing support within the City and the pensions industry
for new pensions legislation.
In particular, Mr Morgan is urging that a new act should contain reporting
requirements under which trustees would have to report their investment
plans to an independent body, such as the Occupational Pensions Board. These
plans would have to be reviewed by auditors at the end of each year and
their reports be submitted to the OPB. Additionally, he is urging that
beneficiaries have an automatic right to receive reports of trustees,
accountants and actuaries.
Mr Morgan declined to be drawn on whether the government has a moral
responsibility to make restitution to Maxwell company pensioners because its
own regulatory system proved faulty.
Pensioners are pressing for compensation, arguing that IMRO's failure to
supervise BIM properly allowed assets to be siphoned off.
</TEXT>
