FT  05 MAR 92 / World Trade News: GE expands its business in India
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID HOUSEGO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Electric, the US electrical and plastics conglomerate, is expanding
its business in India in moves seen as reflecting a more optimistic
assessment of India's prospects by foreign investors.
The group said yesterday it had committed Rs1bn (Pounds 21m) fresh equity
capital this year to new joint ventures in India in electrical appliances,
medical systems, engineering plastics and lighting.
GE is also discussing tie-ups with Indian public-sector companies to make
defence, aerospace and transport equipment. It is bidding to build, own and
operate a 800-900MW power station for Delhi.
'The potential of expansion (in India) over the next 10 years is
unequalled,' said Mr Paola Fresco, senior vice-president (international) in
New Delhi yesterday. Similar opportunities could only be found in south-east
Asia and Mexico.
GE's increased commitment to India could provide a catalyst for other
foreign investors, as had GE's entry into Hungary with the collapse of
communism there.
GE is taking a 40 per cent stake in a tie-up with Godrej and Boyce, the
Indian consumer appliances company, to make washing machines, refrigerators
and compressors, for the Indian market and abroad through GE's sales
network. GE will contribute its share of the Rs1.2bn equity in fresh foreign
funds for a new plant at Malanpur in Madhya Pradesh. Godrej will make its
contribution through transfer of existing plant.
Other new ventures include: a 50/50 joint venture with the state-owned
Indian Petrochemicals Corporation to make engineering plastics for the
electronics, automotive and appliance industries, involving equity capital
of Dollars 36m (Pounds 20.4m); and a venture with Wipro, the Indian
electronics company, to make medical systems with the two sides sharing the
Dollars 10m equity capital.
GE is also involved in talks with two of India's biggest public-sector
corporations over licensing agreements in aersopace, defence and locomotive
technology. In the defence sector, it has been discussing with Bharat Heavy
Electricals the licensing of digital tank turret drives and tank gunner
simulators.
