<TEXT>
Jordan, still officially at war with Israel, yesterday announced plans to
suspend compulsory military service to try to help forge a more
cost-effective, modern army, Reuter reports from Amman.
Mr Sharif Zeid bin Shaker, the prime minister, asked the lower house of
parliament to give the government authorisation both to stop the two-year
draft programme and to reactivate it when needed. The 80-seat house is
likely to endorse the plan on Sunday.
The small army, a major source of King Hussein's power, is widely respected
as a disciplined, well-trained force.
Bin Shaker said lessons drawn from the Gulf war last year showed career
soldiers performed much better than conscripts.
