<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / IoD urges radical economic reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANY directors yesterday urged an incoming government to adopt sweeping
economic reforms based on the application of market forces and the eventual
abolition of income tax and other direct taxes.
The Institute of Directors published its 112-point programme as a challenge
to the main political parties as they prepare their election manifestos. The
tone of the document is uncompromising. It advocates a free market economy
untrammelled by subsidies or any government interference.
Among the more provocative recommendations are the abolition of capital
gains and inheritance taxes as well as income tax, the privatisation of all
remaining state-controlled enterprises - including motorways  - and the
introduction of tax relief on health insurance and private education.
The document only has a prospect of acceptance by a Conservative
administration. Even there, support could be less than total.
The institute, under Mr Peter Morgan, its director-general, and his
predecessor Sir John Hoskyns, is regarded as one of the more influential
policy organisations of the right, although it has no direct political
affiliation.
However, there is an assumption that Mr John Major is not as keen on some of
the IoD's ideas as was Mrs Margaret Thatcher.
Mr Morgan said at a London press conference yesterday that a refocusing of
the balance between government, markets and the individual was the theme of
the document. 'It outlines what company directors want the new government to
do and what they do not want it to do.'
He said: 'Their adoption will create favourable conditions in which
directors can lead their businesses and create wealth. The prosperity of
everyone in the UK depends on their success.'
A complete overhaul of the tax system would include establishing a single
rate of income tax. This would fall to 20p in the next parliament and
subsequently be abolished altogether. The cost of abolishing a range of
direct taxes would be met by limiting the growth of public expenditure to
half the growth in the economy.
Two new government departments are advocated, one for the market, based on a
reformed Trade and Industry Department, and the other for human resources,
responsible for ensuring education, training and employment policy is geared
to individual needs.
David Owen writes: Labour last night called on Mr Major to make clear which
of the institute's proposals enjoyed Conservative support, warning that
voters would 'seriously suspect' the manifesto was the party's 'secret
agenda'.
Forward to Prosperity: a business leaders' manifesto for the next
government. Director Publications, Mountbarrow House, 6-20 Elizabeth Street,
London SW1W 9RB. Pounds 25.
</TEXT>
