FT  04 MAR 92 / Parliament and Politics: Nadir payments to Tories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Asil Nadir secretly transferred at least Pounds 130,000 in donations to
the Conservative Party during the 1980s from companies within his Polly Peck
business empire, Andrew Jack writes.
A team led by Mr Christopher Morris of accountants Touche Ross, one of the
joint administrators of Polly Peck International, unearthed cheques drawn on
companies within the Polly Peck group between 1985 and 1990. None of the
donations was disclosed in the accounts for the years concerned.
Mr Nadir, who was chairman of PPI, currently faces 66 charges of fraud and
false accounting.
It has been known for some time that Mr Nadir made donations to the
Conservatives but it had previously been believed that these were made
solely from his own money.
Touche Ross confirmed last night that it had identified donations from Polly
Peck companies soon after the group went into administration.
Mr Morris has been advised that nothing can be done to recover the money.
Company legislation requires that political and charitable contributions
made by companies are disclosed in the annual report and accounts. However,
the DTI was unable to confirm last night whether these disclosure
requirements cover subsidiary companies or simply the parent.
</TEXT>
