<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / Parliament and Politics: Backstage anger as leaders clash
over NHS - Prime Minister's Questions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRAYING TEMPERS and mounting campaign fatigue were clearly in evidence at
Westminster yesterday as the party leaders again clashed over the National
Health Service and party officials traded insults over behind-the-scenes
smear stories.
At what many MPs believed would be the third-last prime minister's question
time before the general election, Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, tried
to link alleged underfunding of the NHS with widely anticipated Budget tax
cuts.
Quoting a consultant cardiologist at Guy's Trust Hospital, he said that
doctors were now turning away patients on the grounds that funding for their
operations was unavailable.
Mr Kinnock went on to charge the prime minister with planning to borrow for
tax cuts when the voters' wanted available resources spent on health and
other public services.
'You want to bribe. They want to build. Why don't you listen to them?' he
asked, to a chorus of cheers from the Opposition backbenches.
Mr John Major responded angrily that while the Conservatives had raised NHS
spending beyond the rates promised in the 1987 Labour manifesto, his
opponent still refused to reveal how much he would spend on health.
'Your priorities do not add up and you know it,' he told the Labour leader.
'You can't put a cost on your compassion for it is bogus.'
The exchange came after Labour had launched a fresh assault on the Tories by
publishing an opinion poll on attitudes to the Tory record along with
forecasts purporting to illustrate how living standards would deteriorate if
the Conservatives won a fourth term.
The attack was immediately undermined by the revelation that one key figure
was wrong. The claim that 79 per cent of those polled believed their
financial situation had got worse over the last 13 years had been subtitled
with the slogan Conservative Britain: they'll never get it right.
In fact, to Labour's embarrassment, the figure was a misprint that should
have read 39 per cent - provoking a jubilant Conservative Central Office to
charge their rivals with running a gaffe-ridden campaign.
Fewer than one in three staff in tax offices say they will vote for the
Conservative party at the coming election, according to a survey by the
Inland Revenue Staff Federation.
Some 45 per cent of a 1,000-member poll, carried out by Mori, said they
would vote Labour, 31 per cent Conservative and 19 per cent Liberal
Democrat.
IRSF officers believe the figures represent a marked shift towards the
opposition parties.
</TEXT>
