FT  04 MAR 92 / Parliament and Politics: King attacked over BAe order -
Defence Questions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR MPs accused the government in the Commons yesterday of using orders
for defence equipment to strengthen the position of Conservative MPs in
marginal constituencies at the coming general election.
Mr Tom King, defence secretary, announced that the decision to place a
Pounds 570m contract with British Aerospace Defence for the development and
initial production of its advanced short range air-to-air missile (Asraam)
would 'safeguard' 7,000 jobs.
Mr Robert Hayward, who won his Kingswood constituency with a majority of
1,797 at the last general election, and Mr David Sumberg, returned for Bury
South with a majority of 3,720, were among the Tory backbenchers who warmly
welcomed the announcement.
The minister stressed that the contract would bring welcome work not only to
British Aerospace Dynamics Division factories in Stevenage and Lostock near
Bolton, but also to its principal sub-contractors Hughes at Glenrothes in
Scotland, Royal Ordnance at Kidderminster, Thorn EMI at Feltham, and Lucas
at Bradford.
Mr Patrick Ground (C Feltham and Heston), who did not participate in the
exchanges, had a majority of 2,148.
Mr Martin O'Neill, shadow defence secretary, pointed out that the
announcement had come too late to save the jobs of 450 BAe employees who
were told last month they were to be made redundant.
In more strident tones, Mr Dennis Skinner (Lab Bolsover) said the
announcement had not really been about defence but about 'Tory marginals'.
Mr King hit back by condemning the 'hypocrisy' of Labour MPs, whose party
had voted for 'huge cuts' in defence expenditure and then criticised the
government.
The minister won further cheers from the Conservative benches when he told
the House that HMS Vanguard, the first of the Trident submarines which are
to replace the Polaris nuclear deterrent force, was set to roll out of the
Devonshire Dock Hall in Barrow today.
He confirmed that contract negotiations with Vickers Shipbuilding and
Engineering for the fourth Trident submarine were under way.
