FT  04 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Tories determined on Schools Bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is deter-mined to get the Schools Bill through parliament
before the election in spite of the defeats in the Lords, Mr Kenneth Clarke,
the education secretary, said yesterday.
Privately, ministers sounded unruffled by the setback. If they lost the
bill, or this element of it, because of lack of time before the general
election, an incoming Tory government could re-introduce it immediately
afterwards.
Mr Clarke was adamant that the bill would become law in a 'sensible,
workable form', and emphasised that his priority was getting the parent's
charter through, including performance league tables for schools.
Peers decided on Monday night that the chief inspector of schools, rather
than individual governing bodies, should decide who should carry out
inspections and that local authorities should still be able to inspect
schools they maintain.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, was said to be 'disappointed' at the
decisions.
The government could try to overturn the defeats at the bill's report stage
next Tuesday, or use the opportunity to dilute the involvement of the chief
inspector. The provisional date for the final Lords stage is Monday March
16, but if an election was announced before then it could be taken earlier.
Labour believes that it will benefit politically whatever ministers do.
Either the government is defeated - through trying unsuccessfully to insist
on its way or by having to compromise - or it is seen to be behaving
high-handedly in pressing ahead with an unpopular policy.
