<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Credit-card issuers act to stem Pounds
165m-a-year fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS AND building societies yesterday started a campaign to combat
credit-card fraud following a 35 per cent surge in the crime last year.
Mr Kenneth Baker, the home secretary, said that credit-card fraudsters stole
Pounds 165m last year. 'By reducing the attraction of cards as a soft target
we can do much to reduce these crimes,' he said at the launch of the Card
Watch campaign.
According to the Association for Payment Clearing Services, which has
organised the campaign, leading banks and building societies have issued
more than 80m plastic cards. At least 2m are stolen each year, an average of
5,500 a day. Most thefts take place at work, but other target areas are cars
and the home.
The initiative, part of a three-year programme, involves increasing public
awareness and the introduction of more sophisticated technology such as
digital signatures, fingerprint recognition and personal identification
numbers for shop transactions.
Mr Baker said that the initiative would make it harder for thieves to get
hold of cheque and credit cards by improving the delivery of new cards and
by making it easier for cashiers and shopkeepers to check the identities of
users.
Mr Jim Parsons, the association's head of fraud prevention, said that lost
or stolen cards accounted for 75 per cent of fraud losses and cards that did
not reach the genuine customers 20 per cent. The remainder was accounted for
by fraudulent applications and counterfeit cards.
'There is no single solution to beating this serious crime,' said Mr
Parsons. 'The battle against card fraud must be waged on many fronts and we
are investing heavily on a wide range of initiatives.'
The anti-fraud campaign includes increasing the number of transactions in
retail stores which require authorisation, developing a comprehensive file
of more than 3m 'wanted' cards, and using computer systems that would detect
unusual spending patterns on accounts before a card is reported missing.
</TEXT>
