<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Sparks with a tough at the top - Paul
Gallagher, new EETPU general secretary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Mr Frank Chapple left the general secretary's job at the EETPU
electricians' union after a controversial tenure, he predicted that his
successor would carry on the tradition. 'If you think I'm rightwing, wait
until you see Eric Hammond.'
Eight years later Mr Hammond says the same about Mr Paul Gallagher, who
takes over from him next week. The view is expressed only half-seriously,
with the broad grin that accompanies many of Mr Hammond's pronouncements.
Political differences between right and left in unions have become less
pronounced since the Labour party's move to the political centre.
Nonetheless many believe the type of trade unionism symbolised by the EETPU
remains a threat to traditional union values.
Mr Gallagher's stewardship of the union will have effects far wider than the
360,000 EETPU members. The union and the AEU engineers will today announce
the outcome of a merger ballot. If the result is positive they will unite to
form Britain's second-largest union, with 1m members.
Mr Gallagher, 47, will be in a strong position to become general secretary
after the new union draws up a constitution. In any event, he will have a
strong influence on employees' relations with their employers and on whether
trade unions can present a more united front than in recent years.
The EETPU was expelled from the Trades Union Congress in 1988 after a series
of rows culminating in its refusal to accept a congress instruction to
withdraw from two single-union deals. If there is a 'yes' vote today, the
AEU-EETPU will talk with the TUC about affiliation.
What kind of man will the TUC - and the employers he will deal with  - find?
The son of a dustcart driver and a home help, Mr Gallagher left school at 15
and qualified as an electrician four years later. In the meantime he joined
and left the Communist party. That had a significant effect and he became a
firm opponent of the political creed he once believed in.
'When I first joined the EETPU I would sort of stand up in the branch and
advocate we hang Frank Chapple and fight for Utopia. And then I learnt some
sense. I became alarmed at the way I perceived the trade union movement
being used by leftwing and Communist elements and decided that communism
would be bad for the UK.'
In the EETPU Mr Gallagher found the right home. Following ballot-rigging
scandals in the late 1950s it had banned Communists from holding posts and
was firmly in the control of the right. Mr Gallagher had carte blanche to
harry his political opponents. In a typical example, at a TUC conference in
1983 he accused Mr Arthur Scargill of being a 'boot-licker' and
'contemptible' after the miners' leader made a trip to Moscow.
Mr Gallagher's abusive verbal style, as much as his politics, has earned him
the suspicion, and sometimes contempt, of opponents, some of whom believe it
to be the product of shyness. He is a constant smoker and sometimes appears
nervous. One union general secretary says: 'He is a thug. He bawls and he
shouts. He is liable to blow up at any time. Someone has told him that it is
clever to be nasty.'
Supporters say his abrasive exterior belies his compassion. A colleague
says: 'When you gain his confidence he backs you to the hilt. He worries
about the welfare of people he works with and that helps explain why he has
built up a loyal feeling within the EETPU. But whereas Eric Hammond is
laconic and controlled, Paul can sometimes speak without thinking first and
his sarcasm can be quite hurtful.'
The verbal pugilism stems in part from his background in the union. His rise
in the EETPU began when at 22 he became an officer in the Manchester branch,
dealing with electrical contracting.
Mr Ian Brown, a former colleague who left the union after its expulsion from
the TUC, says: 'Contracting is a rough, tough environment. Work in
contracting is often casual and that leads to casual attitudes. You do not
get any respect unless you operate like Gallagher. He is no different from
many other people in the industry.'
He is well respected in the industry. Mr Harry Simpson, director of the
Electrical Contractors Association, says Mr Gallagher represents members
well. 'The EETPU are most effective bargainers and Paul Gallagher is in that
mould. They do their homework and they can quite often win a better deal
than would other, less well-trained and well-prepared unions.'
Mr Simpson praises Mr Gallagher for his role, as president of the union
since 1986, in setting up three ECA-EETPU joint companies to provide
temporary labour for the industry, and pensions and training for workers.
It is this type of partnership with employers that has earned the distrust
of other unions. In party terms Mr Gallagher is not far removed from many
other trade unionists. 'I find myself on most counts now sitting very
comfortably with the policies of the Labour party,' he says.
What irked the left most about the EETPU in the 1980s was its challenge to
traditional ideas of what a union should do. Some found its flaunting of
offers of financial and other services to members to be a distraction from
the main business of a union. Most were alarmed when it accepted government
money for leadership elections. Only the AEU opposed its expulsion from the
TUC.
The differences are less stark now. Other unions have moved towards the
EETPU way of thinking on service provision. Most take part in 'beauty
contests' for single-union deals.
The main difference is in the leadership. In the controversies of the 1980s
the EETPU was led by a supremely confident man. Mr Hammond revelled in the
intellectual challenge of taking on his opponents.
Mr Gallagher, sharp-witted but not an original thinker, would be less
comfortable if faced with the kind of animosity directed at Mr Hammond. Most
colleagues believe he wants to find a way back into the trade union
mainstream. One colleague says: 'He is much more a man of the movement than
Eric.'
Mr John Aitkin, leader of the Electrical Plumbing and Industries Union, an
EETPU breakaway, is sceptical. 'The view is that Gallagher will be more
pliable than Hammond. But then they said that about Hammond when he took
over from Chapple, and look what happened with him.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
