<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / Tories redraw post-election plans for BR sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HEAVILY revised plans for the privatisation of British Rail are likely to be
published soon after the general election in the event of a Conservative
victory.
The plans, which have been agreed by ministers, represent a defeat for the
approach favoured by Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the transport secretary. But
details are unlikely to appear in the Conservative party manifesto for fear
that they could lose more votes than they win.
Instead, the manifesto will focus on the shorter-term objective of ending
BR's statutory monopoly on railway services and encouraging the private
sector to run trains in competition with BR.
Since Mr Rifkind first announced plans to end BR's statutory monopoly
several private-sector operators, such as Virgin Group, Orient-Express
Hotels, Stagecoach Holdings and National Power, have expressed strong
interest in running their own passenger or freight trains.
The manifesto will stress that opening BR's tracks to these operators will
bring an increase in the number of trains running on BR because existing
services, including subsidised ones, will continue.
A white paper preparing for privatisation was to have appeared by the end of
last year but was held up by ministerial differences over the best way to
proceed.
The centrepiece of Mr Rifkind's much-leaked plan was a speedy sale of the
profitable InterCity and Railfreight sectors complete with tracks and
trains. Other ministers - notably Mr Peter Lilley, the trade and industry
secretary - argued that if companies operating trains also owned the tracks
they would inevitably try to inhibit competition from other entrants.
Mr Lilley and his allies have successfully argued that all BR's tracks
should be put into the ownership of a single central body which will open
them up to BR or any private-sector companies wanting to run trains on them.
BR's four operating divisions - InterCity, Railfreight, Network SouthEast
and Regional Railways - will then be sold to the private sector without
their tracks as each becomes profitable.
The four divisions' profits will be boosted by stripping out unprofitable
but socially necessary services and putting them out to tender, with
franchises going to whichever private operators require the smallest subsidy
to operate them.
Fair play between former BR operating divisions and new private-sector
competitors will be supervised by a regulatory authority such as those
already operating in the other former nationalised industries.
Delaying publication of the plans until after the general election will
avoid any embarrassing climbdown by Mr Rifkind, who faces a tough electoral
battle to retain his marginal Edinburgh Pentlands seat. If he is re-elected,
awkwardness could be avoided if he was given a new post in a cabinet
reshuffle.
</TEXT>
