<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / Talks fail to end TV listings row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEGOTIATIONS involving a number of secret offers between the BBC and
newspaper and magazine groups to try to reach agreement on payments for
television listings information have failed.
The issue will now be settled by the Copyright Tribunal, which is finalising
its decision on copyright fees for programme listings. It is due to make an
announcement later this month after holding a hearing from November 12 to
December 20 last year.
A number of publishing organisations had complained that the broadcasters'
fees were too high. The organisations were the Newspaper Publishers
Association (NPA), representing national newspapers; the Newspaper Society,
representing regional newspapers; Time Out, the London listings magazine;
Hello, the celebrity magazine; and the Surrey Advertiser group.
While the tribunal has been deliberating on its verdict BBC Enterprises, the
BBC's commercial arm, has made a number of 'without prejudice' offers to
publishers. These were rejected, even though they envisaged lower payments
than the corporation had initially sought.
The NPA offered both the BBC and ITV a deal that would involve a single
annual payment enabling national newspapers to carry seven-day listings of
television programmes. This in turn was rejected by the broadcasters.
The wrangle follows the government's decision to end the duopoly enjoyed by
Radio Times and TV Times magazines in the television listings market, and to
give all publishers access to all programming listings in return for a
copyright fee.
Since the new regime began in March last year, most publishers have been
paying the BBC and Independent Television Publishers, holder of ITV
programmes copyright, only a token sum of Pounds 250 a year.
Once the Copyright Tribunal has ruled, the actual fees will be backdated to
March last year.
After the government's decision the BBC initially proposed 10 different band
rates for weekly and daily papers. These ran from Pounds 600 a year for a
weekly with a circulation of 11,000, to Pounds 210,000 for a national daily
with sales of more than 1.7m.
While the Copyright Tribunal had been considering its decision some national
newspapers have launched seven-day television listings supplements. This,
the BBC has argued, proves how valuable television-listings copyright is.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
