<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / Lloyd's wins court ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER, ANDREW JACK and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S of London yesterday won a move to have a legal dispute between it
and several hundred Names transferred to the Commercial Court.
The Names - individuals whose assets support underwriting at the insurance
market - seek injunctions to stop Lloyd's drawing on their deposits to meet
cash calls. They had wanted the case to be heard in Chancery Court.
Judge Mervyn Davies refused Mr Michael Freeman, the solicitor for the Names,
automatic leave to appeal against the decision.
Mr Freeman said last night: 'It would be a waste of time to appeal the
decision. We really want to get on with it.'
He said Chancery was the most appropriate court to consider the case because
of its trust implications. Lloyd's argued that the Commercial Court had most
experience of dealing with these matters.
The case will go to the Queens Bench, but Lloyd's said yesterday that
subsequent transfer to the Commercial Court would be a formality.
Hearings in the case, in which about 720 Names have issued motions for
injunction against members' agents, are due to take place at the end of this
month.
Lloyd's said yesterday that 300 syndicates named in a suit brought by 91 US
Names were seeking to have the case thrown out. The Names allege that
Lloyd's had breached securities laws and legislation against racketeering in
the US.
The syndicates say they cannot be sued because they are not legal entities.
Meanwhile, Mr David Coleridge, Lloyd's chairman, has consented to make
available to members comprehensive details of the composition of Lloyd's
syndicates.
In a letter to Sir William Clark MP, Mr Coleridge said Lloyd's would give
all members access to 'information about the number of working and external
Names on every syndicate and the aggregate values of those participating for
each of the last six years'.
</TEXT>
