<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / West European car sales expected to fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WEST EUROPEAN new car sales are expected to fall to around 13.2m this year
from 13.42m in 1991, Mr Robert Eaton, president of General Motors Europe,
said yesterday. GM Europe, one of the least protectionist car makers in
western Europe, also signalled significant toughening of its stance against
the Japanese car industry.
While Japanese productivity was high, there was 'reason enough' for the
European car industry to 'maintain its self-confidence,' he said. 'There is
no reason to believe the future of the European industry will depend on
copying Japanese systems. Europe should stop placing the Japanese car
industry on a pedestal.'
In an attack on the Japanese industry, Mr Eaton claimed that Japanese car
makers benefited from 'different cultural, social and societal systems,
lower wages and longer working hours, the long-standing support of and close
co-operation with their government, import barriers that protected their
national industry and profitability for decades, and which are only now
being gradually removed.'
Mr Eaton said UK new car sales were forecast to rise in the second half of
the year to 1.7m compared with 1.59m last year. Sales in Germany were
expected to fall by around 13.5 per cent to some 3.6m from 4.16m in 1991.
Rover, the UK vehicle maker, yesterday took the unusual step of unveiling
two new cars simultaneously, a coupe version of the Rover 800 executive
saloon and a convertible version of the smaller Rover 200, at the Geneva
show. The unveilings mark the start of an expected flurry of new products
from Rover Group this year, to include the first MG two-seater sports model
since the Abingdon factory which produced the MGB closed a decade ago.
Late rally helps Ford, Page 7
