<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / BTR drops plan to create global engineering business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER and ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BTR, the UK industrial conglomerate, has dropped plans to create a global
electrical engineering business in the wake of its victory last November in
the Pounds 1.5bn takeover of Hawker Siddeley.
BTR's plan to form such a business, with worldwide annual sales of Pounds
750m, surfaced during the closing stages of the fiercely contested bid
battle. At the time, Hawker executives derided the plan's logic.
In their first interview since capturing Hawker, BTR executives said senior
Hawker managers had persuaded them not to merge the company's electric
motors, transformers, switchgear and railway signalling businesses. The
proposal had also been met by City scepticism during the bid.
Mr Robert Faircloth, BTR's new chief operating officer who is supervising
the integration of Hawker, said: 'We took poetic licence to change our mind
on some of these things.'
He now believes that large electric motors, transformers and switchgears
form a coherent business. Signalling and other railway electrical equipment
will stay in the rail business, because of the shared customer base.
BTR says that rail is one area where it feels it will be necessary to form a
'strategic alliance' with another big group to survive in the competitive
world market. Mr Alan Jackson, BTR's chief executive, angrily denied a
recent report that he was still considering selling Hawker's rail equipment
division to Siemens, the German electrical group.
Hawker had reached an advanced stage in talks regarding the sale of its rail
business to Siemens. As part of its defence, Hawker unveiled plans to sell
60 per cent of its business and focus on three core operations - aerospace,
electric motors and batteries.
Mr Jackson said BTR was not discussing with anyone the disposal of any
Hawker assets, adding: 'The damage this sort of report has done to morale
inside the company is considerable.' Mr Faircloth said he still had an open
mind as to whether any business would be sold. Mr Jackson suggested that BTR
might end up retaining more than the 80 per cent of Hawker as mooted during
the takeover.
BTR achieved much of its success in the 1980s through rigorous profit
planning and has moved quickly to inform Hawker companies of its profits
record and expectations.
Mr Faircloth said many of Hawker's businesses were still losing money and
would need to shed many jobs, a process which had already started. He
declined to give specific figures before BTR's annual results next
Wednesday.
Mr Faircloth paid tribute to the positive attitude of Hawker staff following
the takeover. But, he said: 'The message had to go across that a large
organisation with great turnover, but generating no profit, is a meaningless
situation as far as BTR goes.'
</TEXT>
