<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / Bush suffers fresh blow in US primaries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush suffered another setback yesterday as Mr Pat Buchanan,
his rightwing challenger for the Republican presidential nomination, won
strong support among party voters in Georgia and Maryland.
In the race to become the Democratic party's candidate for president, two
front-runners emerged: Governor Bill Clinton of Arkansas, who won in Georgia
by a big margin, and former Senator Paul Tsongas of Massachusetts, victor in
Maryland.
Mr Bush won the primary elections of Republican voters in Georgia and
Maryland and appeared assured of victory in Colorado. But Mr Buchanan's
surprising showing turned the results into a Pyrrhic victory for the bruised
president.
In Georgia, where Mr Buchanan had concentrated his campaign, he appeared to
have scored 39 per cent to Mr Bush's 61 per cent with more than half the
polling precincts counted. In Maryland, exit polls and early returns showed
him with more than 30 per cent of the vote, although he had hardly
campaigned in the state.
The outspoken television commentator based his Georgia campaign on a
racially oriented appeal to conservative white voters, but his most
productive theme remained his assault on Mr Bush for breaking his 1988 'no
new taxes' campaign pledge.
Mr Bush yesterday acknowledged that the 1990 budget compromise - in which he
agreed to a tax increase - was one of the biggest mistakes of his
presidency. But he remained determined to interpret support for his
challenger as a protest vote directed at politicians in general, not just
his own record in office.
'To those who have been with me in the past but did not vote for me today, I
hear your concerns and understand your frustration with Washington. I am
committed to regaining your support,' he said.
Mr Buchanan still shows little sign of having a broad enough appeal to win
even a single state from Mr Bush, but his repeated strong showings seem
likely to kill any lingering hopes the Bush campaign may have nurtured that
their irritating challenger might retire from the race.
Instead, he appears sure to remain a thorn in Mr Bush's side right up to the
Republican convention in Houston in August, weakening the president's
efforts to prepare for the November 3 election.
On the Democratic side, Governor Clinton's victory in the Georgia primary
had been anticipated but the margin of victory outperformed expectations.
With 57 per cent of precincts reporting, his tally topped 63 per cent to 18
per cent for Mr Tsongas.
In Maryland, exit polls and early returns showed Mr Tsongas had won an
estimated 43 per cent, against Mr Clinton's 32 per cent. Although the margin
was narrower than Mr Clinton's in Georgia, Mr Tsongas in Maryland was
outside his home region - unlike Mr Clinton in Georgia.
In both states, the three other Democratic hopefuls - Senator Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska, Senator Tom Harkin of Iowa and former Governor Jerry Brown of
California - garnered so few votes that political analysts raised doubts
about whether their campaigns could continue.
But they still hoped their bids would be salvaged by the voting in other
states yesterday: primaries in Colorado and Utah, and closed party caucuses
in Minnesota, Idaho and Washington state. Results from these ballots were
not expected until this morning.
The seven states which voted yesterday account for 10 per cent of the
delegates to the Democrats' nominating convention, to be held in New York in
July. For the Republicans, only five states voted.
</TEXT>
