<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Zinc hit three-month highs on the LME while nickel closed near eight-month
lows. Three month zinc ended kerb trading above Dollars 1,200 a tonne on
short covering and talk of a pay strike at a Mexican smelter. Three-month
nickel touched an eight-month low of Dollars 7,540 a tonne in the afternoon
on trade selling. Talk that Norilsk in Russia has been granted export
licences for 20,000 tonnes of metal and can ship 8,000 tonnes out of its own
warehouses underlined bearish fundamental sentiment. Lead held near 4 1/2
 month highs struck in the morning as speculative interest was attracted by
the current upward move. The market is underpinned by talk of secondary
metal cuts in the US and impending rationalisation in Europe. Aluminium also
advanced, three-month metal moving smartly back above Dollars 1,300 on US
short covering against a background of physical demand. Silver futures were
ahead at midsession in New York, but gains were limited by Monday's news
that Comex warehouse stocks were 1.7m ounces ahead at a record 280,690,354
ounces. That offset a 0.9 per cent rise in US economic leading indicators
which pointed to an economic recovery and a possible increase in industrial
demand for the metal.
Compiled from Reuters
