<DATE>920304
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: S. African gold producers
divided on forward selling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DIFFERENCES between South African gold producers about the merits of selling
gold forward have resurfaced following the publication in a local journal of
an article suggesting that the practice does not pay.
Mr Hugh Munro, formerly chief consulting engineer in Union Corporation, now
part of the Gencor group, claims in in the Journal of the South African
Institute of Mining and Metallurgy that Western gold producers lost Dollars
2.5bn revenue in 1990 through forward sales of gold.
Mr Munro's conclusions have met with a mixed, if predictable, reception.
They have been welcomed by Gengold, which is a reluctant forward seller and
dismissed by Anglo American, the world's largest producer.
Mr Munro says forward sales consist of gold leased from banks at a very low
rate of interest. It is then sold on the spot market, and the proceeds
invested at the US dollar London Interbank Offered Rate (Libor) at a much
higher interest rate.
The difference between these two rates is the gold contango. Over the past
three years has between 3 and 8 per cent.
Mr Munro's claim is that producers overlook the loss attached to enjoying
this contango. His calculations attempt to prove that every extra tonne of
gold sold per annum reduces the price by about 20 cents an ounce.
Based on Gold Fields Minerals Services figures for 1990, Mr Munro calculates
that non-Communist mines would have made a monetary gain of Dollars 2.55bn
in 1990 had they not sold gold forward.
In the article he argues that, if his views are accepted, then forward sales
will diminish and many gold loans will be repaid so that the price of gold
will rise 'fairly rapidly to a level perhaps in excess of Dollars 400 per
ounce,' and possibly as high as Dollars 500.
Mr Gary Maude, managing director of Gengold, said that he supported Mr
Munro's conclusions which 'back up some of the feelings we've had.'
Gengold's approach to forward sales was that they were necessary only in
special cases where a marginal mine was likely to go under if it did not
sell forward, Mr Maude added.
Mr Kelvin Williams, marketing manager for the gold and uranium division at
Anglo American, said his company was sceptical of the reasoning and
conclusions contained in the article. 'The simplistic application of
complicated mathematics to a collection of dynamic factors in the market is
sufficiently removed from reality for it to be fruitless to comment,' he
said.
Two other factors which diminish the worth of the analysis in the view of
Anglo American are the figures on which it is based and the failure to take
account of the impact of paper gold transactions on the market.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 32
</PAGE>
