<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 92 / International Company News: Bank of Spain steps in to rescue
Banco Ibercorp
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of Spain was yesterday forced to rescue Banco Ibercorp, an
investment house linked to several prominent members of the country's
financial establishment.
Financial regulators moved quickly following a series of damaging
allegations in the Spanish press and the breakdown of takeover negotiations
between Ibercorp and Banco Inversion, a rival financial services
institution.
The Bank of Spain said it was intervening in order to 'prevent the grave
financial deterioration' of Ibercorp and to safeguard shareholders'
interests.
Ibercorp's mutual fund deposits have reportedly dropped from Pta3.9bn
(Dollars 37.8m) to Pta1.1bn, and it has been unable to renew credit lines on
the interbank market.
At the centre of the Ibercorp scandal are allegations that the institution
engaged in insider dealing and protected a privileged group of shareholders,
among whom were several prominent public figures.
Yesterday's intervention is especially embarrassing for the governor of the
Bank of Spain, Mr Mariano Rubio, whose share portfolio was handled by Mr
Manuel de la Concha, Ibercorp's co-chairman and a close friend of Mr Rubio.
Mr Rubio presented his resignation two weeks ago but it was turned down by
the government. He then attempted to find a buyer for Ibercorp. Several
leading retail banks turned down the offer.
The conservative opposition party, Partido Popular, has accused the
government of 'covering up' the potential political impact of the collapse
by blocking a parliamentary inquiry into the affair.
The ruling Socialist party had earlier said that an inquiry was unnecessary
because Ibercorp's stockbroking activities were already under investigation
by the CMNV, the securities watchdog.
Banco Inversion's last-minute initiative failed in part because banks
refused to offer Inversion sufficient credit guarantees to mount the
takeover. Ibercorp's book value was also called into question.
</TEXT>
