FT  04 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Militant to seek CPSA leadership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SUPPORTER of Militant Tendency is to seek the leadership of the CPSA,
Britain's biggest Civil Service union, after Mr John Ellis, the current
general secretary, yesterday secured a job with another organisation.
Mr John Macreadie, the deputy general secretary and a Militant supporter, is
thought to stand a chance of success. The favourite, however, will be Mr
Barry Reamsbottom, a candidate for the union's moderate faction.
Six years ago Mr Macreadie beat Mr Ellis in an election for the top job but
lost a second contest after voting irregularities were uncovered in the
first. Militant's influence in the CPSA has declined since then but Mr
Macreadie, aged 45, has a high profile as deputy general secretary.
If elected he would be expected to seek a more confrontational stance in the
124,000-strong union's negotiations with the Treasury.
In recent years the union's moderate leadership has steered through a series
of controversial changes - including acceptance of an element of performance
pay - which have been opposed by Militant supporters. There has been only
limited industrial action in the Civil Service in recent years compared with
the early 1980s.
Mr Ellis was yesterday chosen to succeed Mr Peter Jones, who is retiring in
June as general secretary of the Council for Civil Service Unions, the
representative body for these unions on certain common issues.
Mr Ellis was chosen in preference to the only other challenger, Mr Derek
Stobbs, assistant general secretary at the FDA union for top civil servants.
Mr Macreadie and Mr Reamsbottom are the only declared candidates in the CPSA
contest. It is possible, though unlikely, that Broad Left 84, a faction
which in political terms stands between the broad left and the moderates,
will put up a candidate.
Mr Reamsbottom, aged 43, is a national officer and editor of the CPSA's
monthly journal.
On the present CPSA executive, the moderates have 22 of the 28 seats and
Militant Tendency supporters three.
Control of the executive has in the past been volatile, however, and at
several stages in the mid to late 1980s Militant was in control.
</TEXT>
