<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE International Air Transport Association (Iata) said yesterday worldwide
traffic showed a healthy increase in January in what it described as a
hopeful sign for the recession-hit industry, Reuter reports from Geneva.
According to an Iata statement, international passenger traffic rose by 14
per cent over January last year and freight traffic rose by 10 per cent.
'Worldwide double-digit growth for both passenger and freight traffic in
January is a hopeful sign for the airlines,' said Mr Gunter Eser, the Iata
director general. But he added, 'We have to remember that traffic in January
1991 was depressed by the Gulf War.'
