</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER a break of nearly 70 years, foreign ministers from the 10 countries
surrounding the Baltic Sea will renew historic trading and cultural ties at
a conference in Copenhagen this week, writes Xueling Lin in Copenhagen.
The conference, which opens tomorrow, is expected to set up a regional
organisation, the Council of the Baltic Sea States, to promote co-operation
in a wide range of fields, including political and economic affairs, trade,
the environment, energy and transport.
'The purpose of the Council is to create a political forum which will be the
driving force behind future political development in the region,' said Mr
Uffe Ellemann-Jensen, Danish foreign minister.
The conference will be attended by foreign ministers from Denmark, Germany,
Finland, Russia, Sweden, Poland, Norway, Estonia, Lithuania and Latvia.
